[1] Jamaica: Rotavirus
Date: Sun 22 Feb 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Dow Jones International News, Associated Press Report, Wed 18 Feb
2004 [edited]
Jamaica: Outbreak of Rotavirus Infection In Montego Bay
-------------------------------------------------
A severe outbreak of intestinal rotavirus infection has claimed 2 lives and
is threatening hundreds of others in western Jamaica, mostly children,
officials said on Wed 18 Feb 2004. Most of the cases are in the resort town
of Montego Bay and the 2 who victims died have been afflicted with
gastroenteritis, a severe form of diarrhea often caused by rotavirus
infection, Health Ministry epidemiologist Janice Alexander said. Both of
the deaths occurred in Montego Bay; one was an adult and one was a child,
Alexander said. She couldn't provide more details about the victims.
The latest report shows that 1350 people have contracted the virus since
the outbreak began more than a month ago, with children under age 5
accounting for 935 cases, Alexander said. "It is more severe in young
children because they can get dehydrated very quickly; they get very
serious levels of dehydration which can even cause death," she said.
During 2003, more than 28 000 cases of gastroenteritis were reported in
this Caribbean country of 2.6 million residents, up from about 20 000 in
2002. There were at least 14 children who died from the illness in 2003,
compared to 5 in 2002. The Health Ministry is warning parents to practice
good hygiene with their children to help prevent infection.
Rotavirus kills some 600 000 children under age 5 worldwide every year,
mostly in poor countries, according to UNICEF. Rotavirus is found in feces
and can be spread through food and human contact. Symptoms include
diarrhea, vomiting, dehydration, and sunken eyes. There are no approved
vaccines for rotavirus.
