[2] USA (Maryland): Suspected norovirus, hospitals
Date: Sun 22 Feb 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@prmedmail.org>
Source: Baltimoresun.com, Wed 18 Feb 2004 [edited]
<http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/health/bal-ca.virus18feb18,0,4751965.story?
coll=bal-health-headlines>

USA: Suspected Norovirus Outbreaks at 2 Hospitals in Baltimore
-------------------------------------------------
Carroll Hospital Center had no new cases yesterday of an infectious
[gastroenteritis] virus that sent 10 people to the hospital and sickened a
dozen of the staff over the holiday weekend. "By late Sun evening, things
seemed really bad," said Brenda Kitchen, infection control coordinator at
the Westminster hospital. "We had a lot of staff calling in sick and 10
patients with symptoms."
In addition to dealing with an "unusual number of patients at the same
period of time and on the same unit," the hospital also had 12 employees
out sick on Mon 16 Feb 2004, Kitchen said. The staff affected by the
gastrointestinal virus seemed to be those who worked in the 24-bed
progressive care unit of the hospital. The number of staff absentees was
down to 6 yesterday -- Tue 17 Feb 2004 -- but 3 of those were new cases,
Kitchen said. By late yesterday, 6 of the 10 patients had improved, and
most of them had been discharged, she said.
The symptoms of virus infection begin with nausea, which leads to severe
vomiting and diarrhea. Most of the patients admitted Mon with the virus
were elderly. "It is not life-threatening, but certainly uncomfortable for
the patient," Kitchen said. "But everyone seems to be recuperating." The 4
patients still experiencing gastrointestinal problems yesterday remained
hospitalized and were isolated from other patients, she said. The staff is
wearing masks, gowns and gloves while treating them; their visitors also
must don protective gear. The hospital will continue to take measures to
prevent transmission of the virus for at least 24 hours after the last
patient's symptoms disappear, Kitchen said.
A similar viral illness that spread to dozens of workers at Good Samaritan
Hospital during the past 3 weeks also appears to have peaked, a hospital
official there said on Mon 16 Feb 2004. A few additional employees called
in sick Mon with gastrointestinal symptoms, far fewer than the several
dozen who had reported the illness in recent weeks, the official said. An
emergency notification system had alerted hospitals across the state about
the outbreak at Good Samaritan. Carroll Hospital Center saw 2 patients with
the virus in its emergency room Sat. "We had been alerted about Good Sam,
so we knew something was going on with us when our patient numbers started
to increase," said Kitchen. "10 would definitely be a lot for us."
--
